<section class="intro-slide">
  <h1 id="project-definition-and-documentation">Project Definition and Documentation</h1>

  <h3 id="polonsky--brine-001">Polonsky / Brine-001</h3>

  <p><small></small></p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="project-definition">Project Definition</h2>

  <p><strong>What are some items to consider when defining a project (web or otherwise)?</strong></p>

  <ol>
    <li class="fragment">Goals / Objectives</li>
    <li class="fragment">Success Criteria
      <ul>
        <li class="fragment">measurable values that indicate the success of your project</li>
        <li class="fragment">number of users</li>
        <li class="fragment">page views</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li class="fragment">Target Audience</li>
    <li class="fragment">Risks</li>
  </ol>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="whats-everyone-else-doing">What&#39;s Everyone Else Doing?</h2>

  <p><strong>It&#39;s useful to see what&#39;s already out there or what best practices already exist early on in your project</strong> &#8594;</p>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment">standards - are there standards in your domain for publishing work online?</li>
    <li class="fragment">&quot;competitive&quot; landscape - look at similar projects&#8230;
      <ul>
        <li class="fragment">what are the components that are relevant to your project?</li>
        <li class="fragment">what parts are particularly successful?</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="what-can-a-user-do-on-your-site">What Can a User Do on Your Site?</h2>

  <p><strong>You can use the following to represent what users can do on your site (site requirements):</strong></p>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment">A list of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_story#Format">user stories (simply a list of sentences in the form of <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">as a &lt;type of user&gt;, I want &lt;some goal&gt; so that &lt;some reason&gt;)</code></a></li>
    <li class="fragment"><a href="https://www.pmi.org/learning/library/use-cases-project-manager-know-8262">Use cases</a> - a description or diagram of actors (users) and their interaction with the system</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="visual-design-information-architecture-user-experience">Visual Design, Information Architecture, User Experience</h2>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment"><a href="https://xd.adobe.com/ideas/process/information-architecture/top-5-content-inventory-tips-information-architecture/">Content Inventory</a> - a catalog of information on your site (basically a list or a spreadsheet!)</li>
    <li class="fragment"><a href="https://xd.adobe.com/ideas/process/information-architecture/sitemap-and-information-architecture/#:~:text=Visual%20sitemaps%20are%20a%20hierarchical,(atomic%20unit%20of%20content).">(Visual) Site map</a> - a diagram that shows the pages in your site and their relationship with each other</li>
    <li class="fragment"><a href="https://webstyleguide.com/4-information-architecture.html">Wireframes</a> - a diagram showing the layout and the information present on a page; can be a simple &quot;low fidelity&quot; hand-drawn picture to an actual HTML mock-up</li>
    <li class="fragment">Prototype</li>
  </ul>

</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="tools">Tools</h2>

  <p>Some applications for creating wireframes and site maps (in order of approximate ease-of-use)</p>

  <ol>
    <li class="fragment"><a href="https://balsamiq.cloud/">Balsamiq</a></li>
    <li class="fragment"><a href="https://www.figma.com/">Figma</a></li>
    <li class="fragment">Adobe Xd</li>
    <li class="fragment">Axure</li>
    <li class="fragment">Classic diagramming tools like: Omnigraffle,  Visio, Dia</li>
    <li class="fragment">Basically&#8230; any drawing tools (pen-and-paper, Photoshoph, etc.)</li>
  </ol>

</section>

